<br>
I mentioned my position in the game as a reference point to detail my experience...  Most people who play this game know that experience is the largest factor in this game...  A level 65 character who has played since release and has seen almost every zone in the game is a more knowledgeable player than one that doesn't have the time commitment to even get to level 65.  Most specifically, someone who has played a specific class to 65 is a MUCH better knowledge base than someone who has &quot;seen&quot; said class play.<br>
<br>
QUOTE<br>
Yes, I agree, even a 15 mana spell like Cease costs mana. Does this mean that they are all mana drains? Nope, just that they cost mana. <br>
END QUOTE<br>
<br>
They cost mana, time to cast them, and opportunity cost of swings you missed while casting...<br>
<br>
QUOTE<br>
You RARELY run out of mana if you know what you're doing.<br>
END QUOTE<br>
<br>
As a hybrid, if you aren't running out of mana, then you haven't been half as worthwhile as a warrior. (who incedentaly doesn't need to use mana to be better than the knight at all times when they aren't using mana... ) Similar to a Warrior who doesn't use the KICK/SLAM or TAUNT.  Hybrids are oh so much more than 50% caster now.<br>
<br>
QUOTE<br>
Also, I notice in all of your thread you don't seem to differentiate between your diferent &quot;roles&quot; when discussing mana expenditures. In other words, you try to portray all of your roles as &quot;universal&quot; when they're not. For instance, if you're a tank, then you have a couple of responsibilities. You keep aggro, and take damage. Anything else is a bonus. &lt;snip innate insults&gt;<br>
END QUOTE<br>
<br>
Incorrect...  due to the fact I cannot take or deal damage like a warrior, I must do more than a warrior somewhere or the party was better off with a warrior.  This is a viewpoint issue.  Fluff ignored.<br>
<br>
QUOTE<br>
Again, this is true, the question is how much in order to perform your function in a group?<br>
END QUOTE<br>
<br>
To lock aggro it takes almost all of my casting time, 4 of my spell slots and a large portion of my mana....  I have 3700mana, FT7, before buffs, and at least 15mana/tick at all times.....<br>
<br>
Festering Darkness<br>
Fear<br>
Terror of Thule<br>
Spear of Decay<br>
<br>
One Festering Darkness (clinging took a recent aggro nerf) and a Fear will guarantee me starting aggro, but do NOT guarantee that a mob will stay on me.  My TAUNT button remains in reserve when I need instant aggro, which will be followed by Spear and/or Terror to secure it again.<br>
<br>
QUOTE<br>
Here's where the BS begins to get deep. No one ever promised you an endless supply of mana to do with at your bidding.<br>
END QUOTE<br>
<br>
I never said anyone did...  wanna check out where the BS is coming from?  I said I must choose a role.. almost all of which I am lesser than an equally equipped warrior in the long run... I can exceed a warrior for a short period in many areas... but a few short bursts leaves me OOM and the warrior still riding high.  This is as it should be.  Its called balance.<br>
<br>
QUOTE<br>
When you're tanking, your job is to get and hold aggro, that's ALL your job is. <br>
END QUOTE<br>
<br>
Incorrect.. see above...  viewpoint issue.<br>
<br>
QUOTE<br>
The fact that you may have to hold back on certain dots/taps/debuffs is of no real consequence, nor is it a great encroachment on your ability to play Everquest. No, no one was ever promised to be full time healer and tank at the same time. No one was promised to be full time DPS and tank at the same time. You have to choose your role and your spells accordingly. Otherwise you'd be evn MORE overpowered than you are now.<br>
END QUOTE<br>
<br>
Nor did I ever say I should have infinite... I only said that my uber taunt COSTS something...  and indeed it cost me quite a bit in both skill caps, HP, equipment, and damage potential.  Then I must spend mana and lose much of my flexability (the one thing hybrids were supposed to be good at) in order to have that uber taunt for a short period.  Taunt is one of the few things that NEEDS to be &quot;bursty&quot; and which favors the Knights.<br>
<br>
<br>
QUOTE<br>
And? The point of this statement is? You're right, you're NOT going to have the same skillcaps as a warrior, the same disciplines, because you HAVE mana. The thing is if you foolishly deplete your mana trying to &quot;be it all&quot; then you have only yourself to look at.<br>
END QUOTE<br>
<br>
Wierdly enough, I think we agree here.... I think you are a tad confused.  Hybrids should be better than warriors in short bursts, Warriors should be a consistent bar with which all other classes are measured.  Knights should be about shining moments... Warriors should be about consistency.  My arguement was based in the knowledge that my lower Hp and skillcaps were in trade for my spells... this much is true...  my point was that warriors frequently list everything a hybrids can do, but do not seem to understand that we cannot do them all at once.<br>
<br>
QUOTE<br>
This is where your argument falls apart. This is the shadowknight's weakest argument. Keeping aggro is normally a non-issue. You guys spend WAY too much mana needlessly. You have a taunt button, learn how to use it.<br>
END QUOTE<br>
<br>
I wasn't the guy who said they had trouble with aggro... I am well familiar with my taunt button, and indeed have spent quite a bit of time experimenting with TAUNT and without my spells.  Hybrids use the TAUNT button for the same thing warriors do.... we just have 7 more taunt buttons. (Death Peace has a perma-slot)  I use mana for many things and I think I would be a better source for determining how much mana is &quot;needed&quot; for a shadowknight to taunt over you...<br>
<br>
QUOTE<br>
 Every warrior here can generally &quot;keep&quot; aggro without doing anything other than getting it in the first place. If you're spending too much mana &quot;keeping aggro&quot; then you are the one who doesn't understand how aggro works. <br>
END QUOTE<br>
<br>
Question...  why are we talking about this if you can hold aggro fine enough? Knights are better at it true enough... but we are better at nearly EVERYTHING for the short time we have mana... and then fall off...  Knights are about BURSTS...  I told you if I burst in one area, then I cannot burst as much in another... and I start lower than warriors in almost all areas...<br>
<br>
QUOTE<br>
Lay off the little spell gems, it's easy, mobs tend to stick with who they're aggroed on unless something dire happens. In THAT case, you have the tools at your disposal, but until that point, any mana spent is senseless.<br>
END QUOTE<br>
<br>
Again... viewpoint.  If I do not exceed a warrior in some areas I am less useful than the warrior...  Hybrids are NOT specialists... we contribute in many places or we aren't worth our slot in the party.  Hybrid versatility makes up for our bursty natures.<br>
<br>
QUOTE<br>
That's fine, so learn how to trust your cleric, and your DPS people. <br>
END QUOTE<br>
<br>
Again, since you do everything automatically, sure you can say that...  I have to micromange everything or I am not worth my salt....  I do less damage than a warrior, take more mana to heal, and have no way to become invulnerable while still tanking. (without a chance to be interrupted) Hybrids must work harder in every case to come out equal to a warrior...  That means I have to use mana.  Sure, I can dedicate my mana to doing something (like taunting) but then I am less of a tank, less damage, and have no get-out-of-jail-free like a warrior either.  Its called balance.<br>
<br>
QUOTE<br>
You know, I have *never* in PoP seen a shadowknight stop a group to med. Just doesn't happen. All the straw men in the world about 1 mana per tick mana regen (as though KEI isn't available in every other zone), and whatnot isn't real impressive if you're wasting your mana.<br>
END QUOTE<br>
<br>
We don't stop groups... we just keep going at reduced benefit... better to limp along LOM than make a party stop.  Those are the times we lose aggro just like warriors....  and we deal less damage.. and we are lesser tanks...  Again... I am a better judge than you are of what is wasting mana and what isn't as a Shadowknight.  I actually play one.<br>
<br>
QUOTE<br>
Nonsense, this is where the deception bgins... it'll continue, to be sure, but this is th beginning. You have a BIG reserve of mana,<br>
END QUOTE<br>
