Cily <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=iustus>Iustus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/10/03 3:32 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: no Glatius</span><hr size=1> This is an interesting discussion. I hope you do not mind if I add my perspective. I think some good points have been made on both sides of the issue. Some things in particular came to my attention reading through this thread.<br>
<br>
There was some talk about how the 'gap' between warriors and knights has been dwindled. I think this is clearly true. However, I would argue that it was clearly needed. You can argue that they went to far, but to say that the gap did not need to be closed is to forget how bad it truely was for knights back in the days of kunark. I truely believe that the balance between knights and warriors overall in EQ is better now than it ever has been in EQ, although you could make a good arguement that there was a good balance just after they added the crafted armor quest and crits for warriors (this was a month or so before the plane of fear was released if I recall correctly).<br>
<br>
What is one measure of balance? Well, ideally, I think the following should both be true:<br>
(1) Most groups would prefer a good warrior over a bad knight to tank<br>
(2) Most groups would prefer a good knight over a bad warrior to tank<br>
<br>
Today, I think warriors are a bit more dependant on the players skill in order to be effective in tanking for a group. This is not to say there is not a lot to know to tank as a knight, because I believe there is, but even a bad knight can do 'ok' as long as they know to use stuns for agro. The real question it seems to me is whether this disparity is too extreme. Perhaps it requires too much skill (so there are too few warriors with such skill) for a warrior to tank as well as the average knight? Or perhaps it requires too little skill for a knight to gain and control agro?<br>
<br>
Whatever the solution, I hope it is one that moves closer to the ideal above, where good players are choosen over bad players, regardless of the class. I think it will be difficult to do that, because I think we are pretty close to balanced now, so I hope the change is subtle enough to achieve that goal, without going too far.<br>
<br>
That aside, I would like to make some more specific comments about some issues raised above.<br>
<br>
Timing with the taunt key is incredibly important.  I may be a knight, but I use the taunt key all the time, and as many have stated above, using it at the right time makes a huge difference. As a paladin, the most effective means I have to regain agro when I lose it? The taunt key. Stuns and such are preemptive agro, you use those early to keep your hate value high. Once you lose it, (for example if you are a poor player), then stuns are much less effective for getting agro back. Most of the time, it is the taunt key which flips the mob back to you. Then you throw on the stuns to ensure the mob stays on you. Sometimes, the best thing about a stun is it stops the mob from hitting the enchanter long enough for you to get in a second taunt try.<br>
<br>
There are solutions today for the inital agro problem. Just one is to use root: puller pulls mob, caster roots it when it gets to warrior, warrior taunts right after tash lands, taunts again after slow lands, warrior taunts again when it cycles, root breaks but one of those taunts worked and the mobs is safely on the warrior. This is just about as effective as a paladin casting stuns as a mob is coming in, the only difference is it requires two people (warrior and rooter) to coordinate, rather than one person.<br>
<br>
When you come down to it, the main thing that hybrids bring to an exp group is they can agro better than a warrior. That is the advantage they have for tanking to make up for their disadvangages tanking. I do not think you can take this away. Can you reduce the gap some? Sure, probably. But too far and you end up on the other end of the spectrum, which in my opinion (biased) is worse. <br>
<br>
If you cannot get to perfect balance, then to have one class be a bit more desirable in exp groups, while the other class is a bit more desireable on raids seems like a better compromise than to have the same class be better both on raids and in exp groups. <br>
<br>
There are some warriors who will argue that no other class should be tanking, and that knights should have other things they can do. I am just going to have to disagree with this viewpoint. I think knights should be viable tanks, at least in exp groups. <br>
<br>
Ok, next point, mana issues. At my point in the game, I no longer have any mana issues with agro generation. None. If the only thing I am doing is generating agro, I will never run out of mana. I can generate plenty of agro and still be gaining mana while I am standing, assuming some mana regen buffs (which I always have). There was a time when I would run out of mana a lot when stunning, but at the top end of the game, this is no longer the case.<br>
<br>
And last point, not that it really matters, but a paladin can tank the lower powater mobs, it just takes more than one healer (which I think a warrior might need as well?) The smallest group I have ever done lower powater with is the following:<br>
Paladin<br>
-cleric bot<br>
-enchanter bot<br>
Ranger<br>
-cleric bot<br>
Ranger<br>
We hunted for 5 hours or so, with only a few deaths, and never a total wipeout. (All of the deaths were either from a cleric bot fizzle that was not caught or pulls of more than one mob with bad resists on mez)<br>
<br>
That said, powater (and kedge for that matter), are some places where some of the agro advantage a knight has is negated, because you cannot cast if you are moving at all, and when mobs hit you, they push you. <br>
<br>
-Iustus <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=124361">Duke Iustus</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
Lord Protector of Marr<br>
Tarew Marr<br>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dwelfnvhal>DwelfnVhal</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 89<br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/10/03 6:41 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: no Glatius</span><hr size=1> Thanks for your very balanced response Iustus, we don't (and probably won't) totally agree on where the 'balance' should stand but i can appreciate your more measured approach to this issue.<br>
<br>
Some comments:-<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>There was some talk about how the 'gap' between warriors and knights has been dwindled. I think this is clearly true. However, I would argue that it was clearly needed. You can argue that they went to far, but to say that the gap did not need to be closed is to forget how bad it truely was for knights back in the days of kunark. I truely believe that the balance between knights and warriors overall in EQ is better now than it ever has been in EQ, although you could make a good arguement that there was a good balance just after they added the crafted armor quest and crits for warriors (this was a month or so before the plane of fear was released if I recall correctly).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I and most warriors have no issue with Knights being a good interchangeable choice as Tank for a group SO LONG AS the warrior is not made an noticeably 'inferior' choice.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Today, I think warriors are a bit more dependant on the players skill in order to be effective in tanking for a group. This is not to say there is not a lot to know to tank as a knight, because I believe there is, but even a bad knight can do 'ok' as long as they know to use stuns for agro. The real question it seems to me is whether this disparity is too extreme. Perhaps it requires too much skill (so there are too few warriors with such skill) for a warrior to tank as well as the average knight? Or perhaps it requires too little skill for a knight to gain and control agro?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Lets be honest here, there isn't really all that much skill involved in use of the taunt key. At the most basic level, you don't blow it unneccessarily so that you're waiting for refresh, you keep an eye on how and when the casters tash/slow whatever and are ready to hit it at the correct moment. The warriors problem is that his ONLY means to control aggro is random - totally beyond his control - he can push the odds to favour success but if the roll isn't right he ain't in business full stop. <br>
<br>
Stuns and etc add specific amounts of hate - not an immediate route to top of the aggro (thats taunt) but nevertheless a far more 'reliable' source of hate generation. Given the spottiness of the RNG that reliability (reliability at range also) is often now being considered much more useful than a small advantage in mitigation. Taunt, weapon procs and DPS all require the mob to be in your face, if there is any problem, poor roll, then you have a mob hitting someone other than the tank, taunting off the puller if a slow will be landing shortly thereafter (before taunt refreshes) and indeed the initial intercept required to get into weapons range and generate aggro are good examples of problems that knights can totally avoid via ranged spells. Furthermore taunt is a reactive skill, you can only attempt to regain aggro, you cannot actively maintain aggro where knights can dictate it much better.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>There are solutions today for the inital agro problem. Just one is to use root: puller pulls mob, caster roots it when it gets to warrior, warrior taunts right after tash lands, taunts again after slow lands, warrior taunts again when it cycles, root breaks but one of those taunts worked and the mobs is safely on the warrior. This is just about as effective as a paladin casting stuns as a mob is coming in, the only difference is it requires two people (warrior and rooter) to coordinate, rather than one person.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The other difference is that yet again the warrior player is forced to rely on someone else to be able to accomplish his task, this is a major negative from a psychological standpoint, one likes to exact some degree of control over the job or why bother? <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :\ --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/ohwell.gif ALT=":\"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>If you cannot get to perfect balance, then to have one class be a bit more desirable in exp groups, while the other class is a bit more desireable on raids seems like a better compromise than to have the same class be better both on raids and in exp groups. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This is my one VERY serious disagreement with you (and most other knights). Raids and exp groups are two seperate, entirely unrelated activities. <br>
<br>
Desirability in an exp group determines if you will get to do anything with your time online, when did anyone get turned away from a guild raid because they were 'not the most desirable class'?  Indeed as your own examples show there are many mobs now that don't require a warrior to tank in a raid setting anyway. I find this supposed warrior advantage to be totally unacceptable as a legitimate balancing arguement.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>There are some warriors who will argue that no other class should be tanking, and that knights should have other things they can do. I am just going to have to disagree with this viewpoint. I think knights should be viable tanks, at least in exp groups.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Again most of us have never seriously argued that this should be the case, I don't mind knights tanking, I do mind being marginalised in the one and only role that i can perform. Getting the balance right (if thats possible) is the problem. <br>
<br>
As I've said before i feel more work should be done to allow ALL plate tanks (not just knights) to provide a useful function to the group outside of the traditional MT role...<br>
<br>
Sorry for the rehash,<br>
<br>
Val <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=glatius2>Glatius2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>will kick your @$$</span><br>  Posts: 907<br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/10/03 7:08 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: no Glatius</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>(1) Most groups would prefer a good warrior over a bad knight to tank<br>
(2) Most groups would prefer a good knight over a bad warrior to tank<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Yes, but when you have a situation where a good knight is preferred over a good warrior, that's a problem.  It should be a toss up.  There shouldn't be a clear reason to take one over the other.  This is exactly the arguement that knights have used since Kunark to get their 'needed' upgrades.  If the arguement was valid for them, it's valid for us.<br>
<br>
And whether we care to bring it up or not, EQ is a game.  It's for entertainment.  You shouldn't have to deal with one character type being easier and more fun to play while another character type that performs the same function is harder and more frustrating.  As it stands for many people, myself included, playing a Warrior can be quite frustrating because of the lack of control.  Previously this lack of control was less destructive in it's results, so it was more tolerable.<br>
<br>
As it stands today, when I lose aggro at the start of a fight, all I can do is hit taunt and throw out a shield on the new target.  That's it.  If taunt works, weee, I win!  If taunt fails, I try again.  And maybe again, and maybe again.  I'm basically standing there throwing a pair of dice hoping they come up 7.  Meanwhile the person with aggro isn't just getting popped a bit, they're taking a serious ass whooping.  Maybe they die.  Maybe they just suck up a lot of mana.  But they sure aren't pleased by it.  The healer sure isn't pleased by it.  And I'm sure not pleased by it.  This is not fun or entertainment when it's done on basically an every mob or every other mob basis.<br>
<br>
Yes we know, it can be worked around if the people involved are willing to go to a bit more trouble.  Yet if these people are a pick up group of strangers, why would they want to go to more trouble if you're not the only tank standing around?  Does the Warrior bring something to the table that would justify this additional overhead?  It seems that many classes feel he doesn't.  And frankly, as a Warrior, I don't think we do either.  The Warrior advantages for most Warriors have been seriously diluted.  Our disadvantages have had additional emphasis placed on them so they come to the forefront more frequently.  This really does need to be addressed.  But in a careful and controlled fashion.<br>
<br>
I'm not sure how up to it SOE really is.  I'm just hopeful they'll give it a try.<br>
 <p>The Man in Black: We are men of action, lies do not become us. <br>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=iustus>Iustus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/10/03 1:39 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: no Glatius</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Quote:<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
If you cannot get to perfect balance, then to have one class be a bit more desirable in exp groups, while the other class is a bit more desireable on raids seems like a better compromise than to have the same class be better both on raids and in exp groups. <br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
This is my one VERY serious disagreement with you (and most other knights). Raids and exp groups are two seperate, entirely unrelated activities. <br>
<br>
Desirability in an exp group determines if you will get to do anything with your time online, when did anyone get turned away from a guild raid because they were 'not the most desirable class'? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Plenty of people have been turned away from joining a guild because they are not a needed class for that guild. The most often used example is the fact Afterlife listed on their guildpage for a year they were not recruiting any paladins (because they were useless on raids).<br>
<br>
Perhaps it is the exception, but most of the people in my guild spend most of their online time raiding, not doing exp groups. When your guild raids 10 hours a day or more, there is not a lot of time left over for exp grouping.<br>
<br>
For what I do, desirablity for a raid is much more important than how desirable you are in an exp group. <br>
<br>
So, back to my original point. I am not saying that the goal should be one class should be better on raids and the other better in exp groups. What I said was if you assume that you cannot be perfect, and get them 100% balanced, then it makes sense to make one better at raids and the other better in exp groups, rather than one class better at both. Do you really disagree with this? (I am not saying this as an excuse, I would feel the same way if paladins were needed on raids more and less useful in exp groups than warriors).<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Indeed as your own examples show there are many mobs now that don't require a warrior to tank in a raid setting anyway. I find this supposed warrior advantage to be totally unacceptable as a legitimate balancing arguement.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I can not think of a single boss mob that we do which I could tank on a raid. Can I off tank adds and such? Yes, I can. But the main bosses? No, I cannot. Could I tank some things we finished with 6 months or more ago, sure, probably, but those encounters are beneath us in the challenge involved, we have moved on. I think you will find in most guilds that only warriors are able to tank the hard bosses they are fighting, whatever they are. <br>
<br>
Let me put it to you this way. If warriors were given a 1.5 second 'cast time' ability that generated hate, like a stun, which they could use between swings, but knights were given defensive and evasive would you be happy? As a knight, if this was done, I would feel like I was getting the better end of the deal, but perhaps this is a case of the grass being greener?<br>
<br>
One thing I would like to be clear about is knights consider themselves tanks. In in ideal world, I think knights and warriors should all be equally good tanks, in exp groups <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>and</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> on raids. Different, but equally good.<br>
<br>
I am willing to settle for not being able to tank any ubermob, for the consolation that I am a bit better in exp groups.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Quote:<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
(1) Most groups would prefer a good warrior over a bad knight to tank<br>
(2) Most groups would prefer a good knight over a bad warrior to tank<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Yes, but when you have a situation where a good knight is preferred over a good warrior, that's a problem. It should be a toss up. There shouldn't be a clear reason to take one over the other. This is exactly the arguement that knights have used since Kunark to get their 'needed' upgrades. If the arguement was valid for them, it's valid for us.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I do not see that as the problem. A good knight being chosen over a good warrior is ok, they are both good players. The problem is when a bad knight is chosen over a good warrior. Or if a group doesnt want to take a chance on a warrior, because the good ones are too rare. <br>
<br>
I am not saying that is is not an issue today. I am saying that it is not nearly as bad as some would have you believe. Good warriors are getting chosen for groups all the time. Just read this thread for many examples. <br>
<br>
As many others have pointed out, it may be impossible to get to a point where the choice between a good warrior and a good knight is a toss-up. There will be some min/max players who will say either one or the other is best, given equal skill. This is why I said the test should be a comparison between a bad person of one and a good one of the other. As long as those two conditions are not true, then the two classes are pretty close to balanced. Small tweaks are possible, but care must be taken to not push to the other extreme.<br>
<br>
--<br>
<br>
I would very much like to see a comparison of the dps between a warrior tanking and a knight tanking the same exp mob. It is my suspicion that a warrior significantly more dps than at least a paladin tanking. I know I give up dps in order to tank. Yes, we can cast stuns between swings, but with the fast weapons of today, that is hard to time, and with a lot going on, usually low on my priority list. If my suspicions are correct, simply making the difference more widely known might be a big boost in getting that good warrior chosen over the good knight, at least some of the time.<br>
<br>
-I <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=124361">Duke Iustus</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
Lord Protector of Marr<br>
Tarew Marr<br>
